For one nest a range (of a few days) was provided for the last date of nest check; I have used the midpoint to calculate the exposure period for these nests. One nest with chicks at the day of finding (i.e. exposure = 0 days) excluded.
Exposure period per nest (with known fate only) calculated. For one nest exposure was uncertain and varied between 9-12 days; I now used 10 days. One clutch found on day of hatch excluded.

For one nest a range (of a few days) was provided for the last date of nest check; I have used the midpoint to calculate the exposure period for these nests. Two nests with chicks at the day of finding (i.e. exposure = 0 days) excluded.
For two nests a range (of a few days) was provided for the last date of nest check; I have used the midpoint to calculate the exposure period for these nests.
Both clutches depredated while being completed the day after finding.

For five nests a range was provided for the last date of nest check; I have used the midpoint to calculate the exposure period for these nests. One nest was reported to be depredated said in the comment that the eggs were cold and scattered outside the nest cup at the last check; I have included it as deserted instead. Another nest reported to be "deserted" apparently contained two dead and wet chicks, so I included it as "hatched" instead. Another nest with "all embryos dead" is included in "failed_other_causes". Nests with unknown fate are not included in exposure_days.
All nests have a range (between date of clutch seen alive and date of fate); midpoint taken for exposure days. Two clutches with unknown fate not included in exposure days.
One clutch found with chicks and classfied as "hatched" excluded from #hatched and exposure_days.

All nests have a range (between date of clutch seen alive and date of fate); midpoint taken for exposure days. One nest marked "depredated" was included as unknown_fate according to information in the comments by the researchers. Another nest with starred eggs at the last visit was recorded to have hatched, but I classified it as "unknown_fate". Exposure_days on nests with known fate only.
One of three nests has a range between date of clutch seen alive and date of fate; midpoint taken for exposure days.
Almost all nests have a range between date of clutch seen alive and date of fate; midpoint taken for exposure days.
One (but not the other) nest has a range between date of clutch seen alive and date of fate; midpoint taken for exposure days. Nest cameras used.
Almost all nests have a range between date of clutch seen alive and date of fate; midpoint taken for exposure days.

For two nests a range is given between date of clutch seen alive and date of fate; midpoint taken for exposure days for the depredated nest, but not for the abandoned nest which likely was abandoned on the second last visit when a bird was caught on the nest. Nest cameras used.
Almost all nests have a range between date of clutch seen alive and date of fate; midpoint taken for exposure days. One collected clutch and a nest with chicks marked as "hatched" excluded.

Almost all nests have a range between date of clutch seen alive and date of fate; midpoint taken for exposure days. A range of last visit days is given for a nest while the comment-field is very clear about the exact date of predation, a fate date is included for a nest while a brood with chicks (of unknown/unmentioned age) are seen on that day, if hatched, probably 1-2 days earlier. Nest cameras used.

Almost all nests have a range between date of clutch seen alive and date of fate; midpoint taken for exposure days. A nest classified as "hatched" based on a family with chicks in the vicinity of the empty nest several days after expected hatch date was interpreted as "unknown fate" by me.

Almost all nests have a range between date of clutch seen alive and date of fate; midpoint taken for exposure days. A fate date is included in the range mentioned before, for two "nests" where a brood (of unknown/unmentioned age) was seen 500 meters from the nest (and thus were presumed to have hatched). A date of last visit was given to one nest that mentioned a different known date of depredation in the comment field. A "last nest visit date" mentioned chicks at several tens of meters away from the nest. Nest cameras used.

Two of three nests have a range between date of clutch seen alive and date of fate; midpoint taken for exposure days. Two clutches found with chicks in nest cup, classified as "hatched" in the original source, were excluded by jreneerkens here (from # hatched and exposure_days)

Exposure of one depredated clutch uncertain between 4-6 days; I used 5 days. Nests that were never visited again after finding are excluded (also from "nests of unknown fate"). Nests of which eggs were collected by the researchers also excluded (also from failed_other_causes).
For three nests with an estimated range of exposure days, I have now selected the average.
For two nests with an estimated range of exposure days, I have now selected the average.
